{ @@HeaderStart@@Roeland Pruijssers – Gyula Izsak, Germany 2012@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game illustrates the strength in White’s c4-c5 break and the subsequent queenside attack. } 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. a3 b6 8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3 d6 10. Be2 Be7 11. Rc1 O-O 12. O-O Nbd7 13. b4 Rac8 14. Kh1 Rfe8 15. Qd2 Qb8 16. Rfd1 { So far both sides are following the typical moves of a hedgehog position. Black’s forces are arranged to prepare ...d6-d5, while White is ready to prevent it with his rooks on the c- and d-files. } 16... Ne5 17. Na4 Ba8 { Protecting b6. } 18. Bf1 Nfd7 19. Rc2 Bd8 20. Bg1 Bc7 21. Rb1 { As the reader may notice, the piece arrangement resembles very closely the previous example. } 21... Bb7 { The c4-c5 break would be imminent after the preparatory move Qc1, but this makes things much easier for White.    The break  21...d5 ?  hangs the a6-pawn for no compensation after:  22.cxd5  exd5  23.Bxa6  Rcd8  24.Qc3 !  Qa7  25.Bb5  +-   Instead, Black could have tried  21...Kh8 !?  followed by  ...Rg8  and ...g7-g5;  22.Qc1 !  Defending the rook on  b1  and preparing c4-c5   White is not ready to break with  22.c5 ?  bxc5  23.Bxa6   23.bxc5 ??  Qxb1  -+  23...cxd4  24.Bxc8  Rxc8  25.Qxd4  when chances are roughly equal  22...Bd8  23.c5 !  b5  24.Nb2  d5   24...dxc5  25.bxc5  Nc6  26.Nxc6  Bxc6  27.Nc4 !  ± followed by a3-a4 pressuring the b5-pawn  25.exd5  Bxd5  26.a4  += White’s position is preferable because of the vulnerable a6- and b5-pawns. } 22. c5 { White achieves the thematic c4-c5 break under excellent conditions. Notice how powerful the bishops on f1 and g1 become. } 22... b5 { Hoping to keep the game closed.   Preventing c5-c6 with  22...Qa8  is met by:  23.cxb6  Bxb6  24.Nxb6  Nxb6  25.Nxe6 !  Rxe6  26.Bxb6  ±   Also, opening up the position with  22...dxc5  23.bxc5  bxc5   23...b5 ?  24.c6 !  +-  24.Nxe6 !  Rxe6  25.Rcb2  Rd6  26.Qe3  Qa8  27.Rxb7  ± gives White a big advantage due to the weak a6- and c5-pawns. } 23. c6 { This typical intermediate move must be remembered, as it creates permanent weaknesses in Black’s camp.   Instead  23.Nb2 ?!  gives away part of the advantage after  23...Nc6 !  24.a4  Nxd4  25.Bxd4  dxc5  26.bxc5  Bxh2  27.axb5  axb5  28.Bxb5  += when White is slightly better but the position is complicated. } 23... bxa4 24. cxd7 { Even stronger is  24.b5 !!  which is analyzed separately after this game. } 24... Nxd7 25. Nc6 Bxc6 { But not:  25...Qa8 ?  26.Na7 !  +- } 26. Rxc6 { This is one of White’s dream positions in the hedgehog. The a6- and a4-pawns are nearly lost while Black cannot easily organize any counterplay. } 26... Qb7 { Aiming to trap the rook for two pieces, but this does not help.   More stubborn was  26...Bb6  27.Qxd6  Bxg1  28.Kxg1  Qa7+  29.Kh1  Nb8 !  protecting the a6-pawn, though after  30.Rxc8  Rxc8  31.Rc1 !  ± White still has a big advantage. } 27. Rbc1 Nc5 28. Rxc7 Rxc7 29. bxc5 dxc5 30. Bc4 { 30.Qa5 !?  is strong too.  A rook and two weak pawns are no opponent for White’s strong bishops, and Black resigned on move 57.  Final remarks  1. After the break 22.c5 ! essentially every tactical variation favours White due to his ideal piece arrangement.  2. It is worth noticing how well White’s bishops work from g1 and f1. } *

