{ The previous example was a very convincing win for White, but on White’s 24th move a wonderful thematic blow was missed. The strongest continuation was: } 1. b5 { Opening lines and unleashing the full potential of White’s forces. Black is desperate as the following variations illustrate. } 1... Ba8 { Or  24...Nc5  25.bxa6  Nb3  hoping to block the b-file, but White is ready to sacrifice his queen with:  26.cxb7 !  Nxd2  27.Rxd2  +- Now the a6- and b7-pawns together with the bishops on  f1  and  g1  are far stronger than a queen. } 2. cxd7 Nxd7 { Material is balanced, but White’s coordination is so strong that the game is decided on the spot after: } 3. Nc6 Qb7 { 26...Bxc6  is refuted by:  27.bxc6 !  Qxb1  28.cxd7  Qxf1  29.Rxc7 !  +- } 4. Qc1 { Threatening bxa6 trapping the queen. } 4... a5 { 27...axb5  loses to  28.Na7 !  h6  29.Nxc8  Rxc8  30.Rxb5  Nb6  31.Bxb6.   27...Bd8  offers no relief after:  28.Nxd8  Rexd8  29.bxa6  Rxc2  30.axb7  Rxc1  31.bxa8  =Q  Rxa8  32.Rxc1  +- } 5. b6 { Forcing the opening of lines and making the most of White’s ideally placed rooks and bishops. } 5... Bd8 { 28...Bxb6  is bad because of:  29.Ne7+ !  +-   Also  28...Nxb6  loses after:  29.Nxa5  Qb8   or  29...Qa7  30.Bxb6  +-  30.Ba6  +- } 6. Nxa5 { White is easily winning, and the game could finish after: } 6... Rxc2 7. Qxc2 Qb8 8. Qxa4 Nf6 9. b7 Bxa5 10. Qxa5 Bxb7 11. Ba6 { Winning the bishop, since White is mating after: } 11... Re7 12. Bxb7 Rxb7 13. Rxb7 Qxb7 14. Qd8+ { From the analysis of this position we learn about the destructive power of White’s forces after the queenside has been opened. It is essential to observe how, after this break, White’s rooks on b1 and c2, and bishops on f1 and g1, perform to the very best of their capacity. } *

