{ @@HeaderStart@@Borki Predojevic – Dejan Nestorovic, Sarajevo 2013@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game illustrates White’s queenside break a4-a5 and the subsequent pressure on Black’s a6- and d6-pawns. } 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. Be2 { Note how White does not bother to prevent ...Bb4 with a2-a3.  His idea will be to later push a2-a4 directly, with the idea of achieving the break a4-a5. } 7... b6 { Another option was  7...Bb4 !?  and a possible continuation is  8.O-O  Bxc3  9.bxc3  Nxe4  10.Bf3  Nc5  11.Nb3  where White is slightly better, since  11...Nxb3 ?  as in the game Bologan – Paragua, Tripoli 2004, could be met by  12.axb3 !  with a decisive positional advantage, for example:  12...O-O  13.Ba3  Re8  14.Bd6  +- } 8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3 d6 { An imprecise move order, allowing White to quickly develop a queenside initiative.   Better was:  9...Be7 !  10.O-O   now  10.a4 ?!  is not as good since Black controls the b4-square:  10...Nc6  11.Nxc6  Bxc6  12.O-O  O-O =  10...O-O  11.Rc1  d6  White’s plan of a2-a4-a5 is now delayed since the rook is no longer on  a1. } 10. a4 { The beginning of White’s plan. } 10... Be7 { Preventing a4-a5 with  10...a5 ?  is generally a bad idea since the weakening of the b5-square is far more serious. In this case, after  11.Ndb5  Qc6  12.Qd4  Nbd7  13.Rd1  the d6-pawn is lost. } 11. a5 { Achieving the a4-a5 break at an early stage, thanks to Black’s imprecise opening. } 11... bxa5 { If  11...Nbd7  12.Nb3  O-O  13.axb6  Nxb6  14.Na5  Rab8  15.O-O  Ba8  16.Bd4  += White has a pleasant version of the hedgehog, as he can choose between pressuring the a6-pawn or creating a passed pawn with b2-b4-b5. } 12. Qa4+ Nfd7 13. Qxa5 Qxa5 14. Rxa5 O-O 15. Kf2 { By playing a2-a4-a5, White virtually prevents Black from carrying out his typical plans. Now that the queens are off the board, this is even more the case. So Black must defend passively and hope for a draw. } 15... Rc8 16. Rc1 { Instead  16.Rd1 !?  deserves attention, because after b2-b4, the threats b4-b5 and c4-c5 are much stronger if White’s rooks are doubled on the d-file. For example,  16...Ne5  17.b3  Nbd7  when Black manages to hold by temporarily preventing b3-b4. } 16... Nc6 { Making White’s plans easier.   Better was  16...Ne5 !  17.b3  Nbc6  18.Nxc6  Nxc6  19.Ra2  += though White is still better. } 17. Nxc6 Rxc6 18. b4 { Black’s position is unpleasant. He cannot create counterplay, but must be ready to meet potential c4-c5 and b4-b5 breaks. } 18... Bh4+ { The beginning of an incorrect plan. The bishop was best placed on e7.   It was better to play  18...Ne5 !  forcing White to clarify his intentions on the queenside. For example:  19.b5  Rcc8  20.Ra4  Kf8  21.Rca1  axb5  22.Rxa8  Rxa8  23.Rxa8+  Bxa8  24.cxb5  += White has a small advantage due to his remote passed pawn. } 19. g3 Bd8 { A useless move, as White should bring the rook back to  a2  anyway, in order to double rooks on the d-file.  Even after a better move, Black is still struggling. For example:  19...Bf6  20.Ra2  Rb8  21.Rd2  Ne5  22.Na4 !  ± It is important for White to stay flexible, and to continue preparing either b4-b5 or c4-c5 as convenient. } 20. Ra2 Bb6 { Bringing the king into play with  20...Kf8  does not help as after  21.Rd2  Ke7  22.Rcd1 !  Black’s position is suddenly lost due to the threats c4-c5 and b4-b5. For example:  22...Bc7  23.Na4  f6  24.c5  Bc8  25.b5 !  +-   Better was  20...Be7 !  though after  21.Rd1  ± White has a significant advantage as Black wasted too many moves to realize that the bishop belonged on  e7. } 21. Na4 { Conceptually appropriate, but missing a major opportunity.   Much better was  21.Rd1 !  as Black cannot prevent material loss.  21...Bxe3+   or  21...Kf8  22.c5  Bc7  23.Na4  Ke7  24.Rad2  Rd8  25.b5  trapping Black’s rook  22.Kxe3  Kf8  23.c5  Ke7  24.Rad2  a5  25.Rxd6  Rxd6  26.cxd6+  Kd8  27.Rb1  axb4  28.Rxb4  ± With a healthy extra pawn. } 21... Bxe3+ 22. Kxe3 Kf8 { Black’s task is now much easier, but still he cannot hope for more than a draw. } 23. c5 { If  23.Rd1  Ke7  24.Rad2  Nb6  25.Nb2  Rac8  26.f4  += White is better, but improving his position is not straightforward. } 23... dxc5 24. Rac2 { Also sensible was:  24.Nxc5  Nxc5  25.bxc5  Rac8  26.Ra5  += } 24... Rac8 25. b5 { An interesting alternative. Instead of having a passed pawn on the c-file, White wants to have a dangerous passed pawn on the a-file, further away from Black’s king. } 25... Rd6 { The only move.   Instead  25...axb5 ?  loses an exchange:  26.Bxb5  R6c7  27.Bxd7  Rxd7  28.Nb6  +- } 26. e5 Rd5 { Again the only defence.   But not  26...Nxe5 ?  27.Nxc5  Rb8  28.f4  Ng6  29.Nxb7  Rxb7  30.bxa6  when the a-pawn decides the game. } 27. bxa6 Rxe5+ 28. Kf2 Bc6 { Better was:  28...Rxe2+ !  29.Kxe2  Bxa6+  30.Kf2  c4  31.Nb2  Nb6  += It is unclear how White can make progress. } 29. Nxc5 { Black’s position is now lost after the forced sequence: } 29... Rxc5 30. Rxc5 Nxc5 31. Rxc5 Ke7 32. Bb5 { This is the key. } 32... Bxb5 { A very nice pawn endgame results after:  32...Kd6  33.Rxc6+  Rxc6  34.Bxc6  Kxc6  And Black eventually loses after:   35.Ke3  Kb6  36.Kd4  Kxa6  37.Kc5  Kb7  38.Kd6  g5 !  The game is far from over yet.  39.h4 !   The careless variation  39.Ke7  Kc6  40.Kxf7  e5  41.Kf6  loses after  41...g4  !.  39...Kc8  40.hxg5  Kd8  41.Ke5  Ke7  42.g4  Ke8  43.Kf6  Kf8  44.f4  Kg8  45.Ke7  Kg7  And now White must triangulate with:  46.Ke8  Kg8  47.Kd8  Kg7  48.Ke7 !  And only now is White winning after:  48...Kg8  49.Kf6  Kf8  50.f5  exf5  51.gxf5  Kg8  52.Ke7  Kg7  53.f6+  Kg6  54.Kf8  Kxg5  55.Kxf7  +- It is unlikely that Predojevic analyzed this variation, but he could probably foresee he was winning, and would be able to figure out the details as they arose. } 33. Rxc8 Bxa6 34. Rc7+ { The rest of this game is irrelevant to our purposes, though White won the game convincingly.  Final remarks  1. White’s early a2-a4-a5 break was very powerful, and Black should revise his poor opening sequence to avoid such an inferior position.  2. After White achieved the a4-a5 break, Black’s main problem was his lack of counterplay and the vulnerability of the a6- and d6-pawns.  3. White missed a major chance to win by not attacking the d6-pawn directly on move 21. The tactics were favourable and the game could have been decided quickly. } *

