{ @@HeaderStart@@Pavel Eljanov – Dmitri Jakovenko, FIDE World Cup, Tromsø 2013@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objectives:  1. The position after 18...Rc8 is an example of White’s advantage in the hedgehog once a couple of minor pieces have been traded.  2. The reader should pay close attention to how Black is unable to push ...d6-d5, and hence must remain passive. } 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 c5 3. g3 e6 4. Nf3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 O-O 9. Rd1 d6 10. Bg5 Nc6 11. Qd2 Qb8 12. h3 Rd8 13. Rac1 h6 14. Be3 Rd7 15. b3 Qf8 16. Nd4 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Rc8 19. e4 { This move establishes a hedgehog-type position under favourable circumstances, since the ...d6-d5 break is hard to accomplish and unlikely to succeed. } 19... Ne8 { If  19...Qd8  20.Qe2  Qc7  21.f4  Qc6  22.Rd3  a6  23.a4  += Black will hardly achieve a break, while a kingside attack with g3-g4-g5 has a good chance to succeed.   The break  19...d5 ?  loses a pawn after  20.exd5  exd5  21.Bxf6  Bxf6  22.Nxd5   Of course  19...e5 ?!  20.Be3  gives a stable advantage to White, and is similar to the game Tiviakov – Anand from the previous chapter. } 20. Qe2 Bf6 21. Be3 { White is in no hurry to make further exchanges, as they are unnecessary. White enjoys some space advantage, while Black no longer has enough material to create serious tactical threats. Unfortunately, this move is tactically imprecise as it gives Black some chances for a ...d6-d5 break.   A safer option was  21.Rd3  Bxd4  22.Rxd4  a6  23.Qe3  Rb7  24.a4  Rbc7  25.Rcd1  += when Black faces problems, in similar style to the game. } 21... Qe7 { The trade  21...Bxc3  22.Rxc3  does not help, as after  22...Qe7   22...d5 ?  is refuted by  23.exd5  exd5  24.Bxh6 !  ± since  24...gxh6 ?  loses to  25.Qg4+  23.Rcd3  += White dominates the board and his bishop is far stronger than Black’s knight. He may proceed with the plans a4-a5 or f4-g4-h4-g5 with a big advantage in either case. } 22. Rd3 { An imprecision which could have allowed Black to free his position.   If  22.f4  Bxc3  23.Rxc3  d5 !  and Black releases his position.   Better though was  22.Rc2  since the try  22...Bxc3  23.Rxc3  d5 ?   or  23...Nf6 !?  24.Bc1  followed by  Rcd3  is now refuted by  24.Rcd3  Nf6  25.exd5  exd5  26.Qf3  when White is simply winning a pawn. } 22... Rdd8 { Missing an opportunity.   A better try was  22...Bxc3  23.Rcxc3  d5 !  as after  24.cxd5  Rxc3  25.Rxc3  exd5  26.exd5  Rxd5  27.Rc8  += White’s advantage is rather small. } 23. Qd2 Qb7 { Threatening ...Bxc3 followed by ...Qxe4.   Now  23...Bxc3  is met by  24.Rdxc3 !  d5  25.cxd5  Rxc3  26.Qxc3  exd5  27.e5 !  += with a structural advantage. } 24. f3 Be5 25. a4 a6 26. Rd1 Bf6 { White’s position is rock solid, and Black has nothing better than waiting.   If  26...Nc7 ?!  attempting  ...b6-b5  , then  27.Bd4 !  highlights the weakness of the d6-pawn:  27...Bxd4  28.Rxd4  And now White is winning a pawn after:  28...b5   or  28...Ne8  29.e5 !  ±  29.cxb5  axb5  30.Rb4  ± } 27. h4 { Advancing on the kingside; White intends to follow up with g4-g5. } 27... Rc6 28. Bd4 { White is now ready to attack on the kingside with g4-g5, therefore he must first remove Black’s bishop from f6.   But not  28.g4 ?!  Bxh4  when things are far from clear. } 28... Bxd4 29. Rxd4 Rdc8 30. g4 Rc5 31. Rd3 { The try  31.g5  is worthy of consideration, but after:  31...Qe7   instead  31...hxg5  32.hxg5  Qe7  33.f4  is very dangerous for Black, for example  33...b5  34.Rh1  bxc4  35.b4 !  R5c7  36.Qe3  Qd7  37.Qh3  Kf8  38.Qh8+  Ke7  39.Qg8 !  followed by  Rh8  with deadly threats  32.f4  g6  The game remains complex. } 31... Qe7 32. Qf2 { Black did not resist the pressure and unnecessarily weakened his position with: } 32... g5 { Better was  32...Qb7 !  though after  33.Qe1 !?  += White keeps all his options open   but not  33.f4 ?  b5 !  ⇆ when Black frees his position } 33. hxg5 hxg5 34. Qd4 { ± Black is now in serious trouble, due to the threat of Rh1. } 34... R8c6 { The try  34...Qf8  would be met by:  35.a5 !  bxa5   35...Rxa5 ?!  36.Qxb6  36.Na4  R5c6  37.e5  dxe5  38.Qxe5  ± } 35. Na2 { Threatening Nb4xa6. } 35... b5 { If  35...a5  the b5-square is weakened and after  36.Nc3  Nc7  37.Nb5  Nxb5  38.axb5  Rc7  39.Rh1  e5  40.Qxd6  the endgame is won for White. } 36. Nb4 Rc8 { Or  36...Rb6  37.cxb5  axb5  38.a5  Rb8  39.Rc3  when the passed pawn and excellent piece coordination should secure a win for White. } 37. Nxa6 bxc4 38. Nxc5 cxd3 39. Nxd3 { The connected passed pawns give White a decisive advantage, which Eljanov converted in convincing fashion: White won.  Final remarks  1. The absence of two minor pieces did not solve Black’s space problem, but it did deprive him of the ...d6-d5 break.  2. The d6-pawn proved a serious weakness throughout the game. Black’s main chance to survive was based on the ...d6-d5 break, which White should not have allowed when he played the imprecise 21.Rd3. } *

