{ @@HeaderStart@@Alexander Galkin – Aleksander Delchev, Ohrid 2001@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This fragment of a game is an additional example of the ...Rg8 and ...g7-g5 plan. } 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3 b6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O Be7 11. Be3 Ne5 12. f3 O-O 13. Qd2 Qc7 14. Rfd1 Rac8 15. Rac1 Qb8 { The game has developed as usual and now the real fight begins. } 16. Qe1 Bd8 17. Qf2 { White’s play is imprecise.   A better move order was  17.Kh1  Bc7  18.Qg1  Ned7  where White has an extra tempo compared to the game, and after  19.Nc2  += we have a typical hedgehog position. } 17... Ned7 18. Kh1 Bc7 19. Qg1 { Protecting the h2-pawn. } 19... Kh8 { Black announces his intention to play ...Rg8 followed by ...g7-g5-g4. } 20. Rc2 { A useful piece of advice for players of the white pieces is the following: you should be ready to meet  ...g7-g5  with c4-c5 opening the queenside with counterplay. Therefore, the move  20.b4 !?  makes perfect sense, and after:  20...Rg8  21.Na4  Ba8  22.Rd2  g5  23.c5 !  += White is just in time, and the subsequent complications will probably favour White due to Black’s weakened kingside. } 20... Rg8 21. Rcd2 g5 22. Qf2 Rg6 23. Nc2 { An alternative was:  23.Bd3 !?  (threatening e4-e5)  23...Rg7   but not  23...Ne5 ?!  24.Bxb6  g4  25.Bxc7  Qxc7  26.Be2  gxf3  27.Bxf3  Nfg4  28.Qd4  += when Black does not have enough compensation  24.h3  h5  25.Bd4  Rcg8  26.Nc2  Qd8 !?  ∞ The break  ...g5-g4  is a double-edged weapon due to White’s well-placed bishops. } 23... Rcg8 { Black’s position remains solid and flexible; he could play ...g5-g4 or just prepare it further with ...h7-h5. } 24. h3 h5 25. Bd4 R8g7 26. b4 Qg8 { Further reinforcing the ...g5-g4 break, though this might just be unnecessary.   Black was perfectly ready for:  26...g4 !  27.h4   the opening of the h-file after  27.hxg4 ?  only benefits Black:  27...hxg4  28.f4  Rh6+  29.Kg1  Bxe4 !  30.Nxe4  Nxe4  31.Bxg7+  Kxg7  32.Qe3  d5 !  -+  27...Qd8 !?  The h4-pawn will soon become a serious weakness. } 27. Kg1 g4 28. fxg4 { Keeping lines closed with  28.h4  does not help much after  28...gxf3  29.Bxf3  Qd8  as Black is much better due to the weak pawns on  e4  ,  g2  and  h4.   The try  28.hxg4  hxg4  29.f4  is nearly suicidal after  29...Qh7  30.Kf1  g3  31.Qf3  e5  32.Bg1  Rh6   or  32...Rg4 !?  (and Black’s attack is deadly.) } 28... hxg4 29. Bxg4 { After  29.h4  g3  30.Qf3  e5  31.Be3  Rh7  White cannot even defend the h4-pawn:  32.Bg5 ?  Rxg5  33.hxg5  Rh1+ !  34.Kxh1  Qh7  +-+ } 29... e5 30. Be3 Nxg4 31. hxg4 Rxg4 { Black has achieved another dream hedgehog position and he imposed his advantage in 12 more moves: Black won.  Final remarks  1. Generally speaking, protecting the h2-pawn with Bg1 is somewhat healthier than protecting it with Qg1. However, if White wishes to use the queen for this purpose, he certainly should not lose a tempo by playing Qe1-f2-g1 as in the game.  2. Important: White should be ready to meet ...g7-g5 with a c4-c5 break.  3. Once again, after Black accomplishes the ...g5-g4 break, things do not look good for White in practically every variation. } *

