{ @@HeaderStart@@John Bartholomew – Timur Gareev, USA 2009@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objectives:  1. This game illustrates how Black can carry out a waiting strategy without damaging his position.  2. Black prepares many plans, and speculates with tactical ideas, but does not carry out any of them.  3. Black requires great calculating ability to carry out this strategy, as one slip can give White an overwhelming initiative, probably through a queenside attack. Both sides must constantly check the consequences of both White’s and Black’s breaks in this structure. } 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3 Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O b6 11. Be3 Rb8 { This prophylactic move gives extra protection to the b6-pawn. } 12. Qd2 Bb7 13. Rfd1 Ne5 14. f3 Re8 15. Kh1 { So far both sides follow the standard developing moves. Something to note is White’s awkwardly-placed knight on a3. White would like to transfer this knight to a better square, say after Nc2-d4; but this is not always easy due to the pressure on the c4-pawn. } 15... Bf8 { The premature  15...d5 ?  would be met by:  16.Bf4 !  Bd6  17.cxd5  exd5  18.Nc4 !  Quite an unpleasant surprise!  18...Nxc4  19.Bxc4  dxc4  20.Bxd6  Rc8  21.Qd4  ± } 16. Bf1 { The attempt to improve the knight with  16.Nc2  is met by  16...Qc7  attacking the c4-pawn, since the natural  17.b3 ?!   better is  17.Na4  Bc6  18.Nc3  Bb7 =  is met by  17...d5 !  opening the centre favourably after:  18.exd5  exd5  19.Nxd5  Nxd5  20.cxd5  Rbd8  21.Bf1  Rxd5  =+ Black has gained the initiative. } 16... Qc7 { Again, the break  16...d5 ?  is met by  17.Bf4 !  Bd6  18.cxd5  exd5  19.Nc4 !  ± as in the note above. } 17. Rac1 Ba8 18. Qf2 Kh8 19. Na4 { If White tries  19.Nc2  intending to follow up with  Nd4  , then after  19...Nxc4  20.Bxc4  Qxc4  the optimistic  21.Bxb6 ?  is refuted by:  21...Qc6  22.Be3  Rxb2  ∓ } 19... Qc6 { A more standard reply would be  19...Ned7  but then White could play  20.Nc2 !  followed by  Nd4  , when White’s chances are slightly preferable. } 20. Nc3 { The tempting  20.Nxb6 ?  is refuted by  20...Nfg4 !  when Black regains the material favourably after  21.fxg4  Nxg4  22.Qe2  Nxe3  23.Qxe3  Qxb6  24.Qxb6  Rxb6  ∓ with better chances due to the pair of bishops and weakened dark squares. } 20... Be7 21. Nab1 Rg8 { Black is ready to create active play on the kingside with ...g7-g5. } 22. Bd4 Qc7 23. b4 { A good decision. As mentioned previously, White should try to meet the ...g7-g5 plan with a well-timed c4-c5 break. } 23... Rgc8 { A curious approach; Black was ready to play ...g7-g5, but now simply decides to go for a different plan. It is typically a mistake to waste three moves on a plan and later choose to do something else. But sometimes in the hedgehog Black can afford such a decision due to the amazing flexibility of the structure.   White was well prepared to meet  23...g5  with:  24.Nd2  Rg6   or  24...g4  25.f4  ±  25.Na4  Ned7  26.c5 !  Breaking on the queenside  !  26...bxc5  27.bxc5  dxc5  28.Nxc5  Bxc5  29.Bxc5  Nxc5  30.Rxc5  Qe7  31.Rdc1  ± When the g5-pawn is more a weakness than a strength. } 24. Na4 Nfd7 25. Be3 Qb7 { Black now seems to be preparing a ...b6-b5 break. } 26. a3 Rc6 27. Nb2 Rbc8 28. Qd2 Qc7 { The break  28...b5 ?  does not work well because after  29.cxb5  axb5  30.Nc3  ± the b5-pawn is lost. As it turns out, when White’s knight can reach  c3  so easily and White’s bishop is on  f1  , the  ...b6-b5  break is unlikely to work well. White is nearly winning after  30...Nc4  31.Nxc4  bxc4  32.b5  R6c7  33.a4  due to the connected passed pawns. } 29. a4 Qb8 { It is amazing how Black continues to wait without causing any deterioration in his position. It seems Black has not done anything, however he has carefully analyzed White’s threats, and is ready to meet them. } 30. b5 { This is not the right timing for this break, as the b6- and d6-pawns do not become targets as they did in the game Flores Rios – Hayrapetian earlier in this chapter.   Better was  30.Nc3 !?  and a possible continuation would be  30...R6c7  31.Qf2  Rd8  32.Be2  with roughly equal chances. } 30... R6c7 { Worse is  30...axb5 ?!  31.axb5  since now White has a potential threat Nc3-a4 attacking the b6-pawn. In addition, the potentially weak a4-pawn has been traded. The play could continue  31...R6c7  32.Nc3  Ra7  33.Nca4  Qc7  34.Qf2  Rb8  35.Ra1  with a level game. } 31. bxa6 { In the event of  31.Nc3  a5 !  White does not have any breaks on the queenside and Black may turn his attention back to the kingside by playing  ...Rg8  followed by  ...g7-g5.  For example:  32.Bg5 !?  Preventing Black’s plan momentarily.  32...Bf8  33.Be2  h6  34.Bh4  g5  35.Bg3  Nc5  =+ White’s position is unpleasant in practice, as he does not have a clear-cut plan. } 31... Nc5 32. Qc2 Ra7 33. Nc3 Rxa6 { Black’s strategy has been successful and his position is now preferable due to his strong knights on c5 and e5.  The rest of the game is irrelevant to our purposes, though eventually Black won.  Final remarks  1. This game was a test of nerves for both players. Each player attempted to carry out their plans, but found a well-prepared opponent. If Black had played 15...d5 or 23...g5, he would have reached an inferior position. In turn, White lost his patience and broke with 30.b5, which gave him a worse position.  2. This type of position requires great precision in calculation from both sides, since they must constantly check how to prevent or meet their opponent’s breaks. } *

