{ @@HeaderStart@@Lev Polugaevsky – Borislav Ivkov, Belgrade 1969@@HeaderEnd@@  This game is a classical illustration of White’s ability to asphyxiate Black’s forces after a symmetric transformation. } 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nxd4 6. Qxd4 g6 7. e4 d6 8. Be3 Bg7 9. f3 O-O 10. Qd2 Be6 11. Rc1 Qa5 { We have transposed from an English Opening into a popular variation of the Accelerated Dragon. } 12. Nd5 { This move has fallen out of fashion since 12...Qxa2 offers good chances to Black.   Nowadays  12.b3  is preferred  (and we will see this move in the next example)  or  12.Be2  Rfc8  13.b3. } 12... Qxd2+ { Heading towards an inferior endgame.   Instead correct was:  12...Qxa2  13.Nxe7+  Kh8  14.Be2  Ng8 !? } 13. Kxd2 Bxd5 { 13...Nxd5 ?!  is not good due to  14. cxd5; Black is in trouble after  14...Bc8   or  14...Bd7  15.Rc7  ±  15.b3  e6  16.Bd3  followed by  Rc7.   A good option was  13...Rae8  and after the semi-forced line  14.Bxa7  Bxd5  15.cxd5  Ra8  16.Be3  Rxa2  17.Rc2  Nd7  White preserves a small advantage, but Black has more counterplay than he did in the game. } 14. cxd5 { We have reached the structure of interest. The c-file is open and for the moment there are no natural breaks to execute. This position has occurred 27 times on my database, and White has scored an amazing 80%. } 14... Rfc8 15. Be2 { += A simple approach. White has a stable advantage due to his space and pair of bishops. His plan is to expand everywhere on the board and to eventually asphyxiate Black. The lack of targets, or natural structural breaks, prevents Black from creating counterplay.   Much more common is  15.Rxc8+  Rxc8  16.g3 !  to follow up with  Bh3  , when Black loses control of the c-file. For example:  16...Nd7   16...a6 ?  loses to  17.Bh3  Rc7   or  17...Rd8  18.Rc1  18.Rc1 !  Rxc1  19.Kxc1  followed by  Bc8  17.Bh3  Rc7  18.Bxd7  Rxd7  19.b3  a6  20.Rc1  ± White gains control of the c-file. } 15... a6 { This is necessary sooner or later, to defend the a7-pawn, but now the b6-square is weak.   15...b6 ?  16.Ba6  ± loses the c-file. } 16. b4 { Beginning the queenside expansion. } 16... Kf8 { Black cannot fight for queenside space with  16...b5 ?  as it weakens the a6-b5 chain, and after  17.Rxc8+  Rxc8  18.Rc1  Rxc1  19.Kxc1  ± White is almost winning due to the threat of a2-a4.   The break  16...e6  17.dxe6  fxe6  weakens Black’s position, but secures some space and after  18.a4 ?!   instead White should play:  18.Kd3 !  Nd7  19.f4  +=  18...Kf7  19.a5  d5 !?  Black has some counterplay. } 17. a4 Nd7 18. a5 { Now the a6- and b7-pawns are fixed and represent potential weaknesses in the long term. } 18... Bb2 19. Rc2 Rxc2+ 20. Kxc2 Bg7 21. Kb3 Rc8 22. Bd2 { Black cannot use the c-file.   Note how White refrains from  22.Rc1 ?!  Rxc1  23.Bxc1  in order to keep more pieces on the board. } 22... Bd4 23. g4 { Now White will claim space on the kingside. } 23... Kg7 { Black’s waiting strategy is a big mistake.   Again  23...e6  was correct, as after  24.dxe6  fxe6  25.h4 !  += Black has many weaknesses, but at least he has space to move. } 24. g5 { Fixing Black’s kingside. } 24... Rc7 25. Rd1 Kf8 26. f4 Bg7 { It was not too late for  26...e6 !?  27.dxe6  fxe6  28.Bc4  Ke7  though after  29.h4 !  ± the threat of h4-h5 is troublesome. } 27. Bg4 Ke8 28. Rf1 Bd4 29. h4 Bg7 30. h5 Bd4 31. Rh1 { Throughout the last eight moves Black’s negligent waiting strategy has allowed a powerful kingside expansion. Although there is no clear winning method yet, White’s position is very promising and should be won with correct play. } 31... Bg7 32. Rh3 Kf8 33. h6 { White has found the right plan. Now he will prepare the decisive e4-e5 break, after which Black’s main problem will be the weak h7-pawn. } 33... Bd4 34. Rd3 { White is already winning after:  34.Bc3 !  Rxc3+   or  34...Bg1  35.e5 !  is similar to the game  35.Rxc3  Bxc3  36.Kxc3  Ke8  37.Kd4  Kd8  38.e5 !  (threatening the decisive e5-e6)  38...Kc7  39.e6  fxe6  40.Bxe6  Nf8  41.f5  gxf5  42.Bxf5  Kd8  43.Bxh7 !  When the passed pawns decide the game. } 34... Ba7 35. Bh3 Bg1 36. Bc3 { Preparing the e4-e5 break. } 36... Ke8 { More stubborn was  36...Bh2  though White is still winning, say after:  37.Rf3  Ke8  38.Bg7  Kd8   or  38...Rc1  39.e5 !  dxe5  40.Bxd7+  Kxd7  41.fxe5  39.f5 !  Decisively opening the f-file. The game could have finished with:  39...Rc1  40.fxg6  fxg6  41.Bd4  Re1  42.Bb6+ !  Nxb6   or  42...Ke8  43.Bxd7+  Kxd7  44.Rf8  to follow with  Rd8#  43.axb6  Ke8  44.Rc3  Rxe4  45.Be6 !  Checkmate is unavoidable. } 37. e5 { +- } 37... Bh2 { 37...dxe5  38.fxe5  Bh2  doesn’t help due to  39.d6 !  breaking through the defence.  39...exd6  40.exd6  Rc6  41.Re3+  Kd8  42.Re7  Rxd6  43.Rxf7  and after  44.Rxh7  the game is decided. } 38. exd6 exd6 39. Re3+ Kd8 40. Re4 { More direct was:  40.Bxd7  Rxd7  41.Bf6+  Kc7  42.Re8  Bxf4  43.Rh8  +- } 40... Bg1 41. Bxd7 { Black resigns, as there is no hope following:  41...Rxd7   or  41...Kxd7  42.Bf6  with the deadly threat  Re7  , and if  42...Kc8  then  43.Re8+  Kd7  44.Rd8#  42.Bf6+  Kc7  43.Re8  followed by  Rh8xh7  winning.  Final remarks  1. Black’s opening was rather imprecise, leading directly to an unfavourable endgame. Nowadays 12...Qxa2 is the move of choice and in fact White no longer plays 12.Nd5 because of this reply.  2. The endgame resulting after move 14 was indisputably superior for White, and the defence was very difficult in practice.  3. Black’s best approach would have been to break the powerful d5-e4 chain with a timely ...e7-e6 break. This weakens the d6- and e6-pawns, but it is the lesser of two evils. Instead, by defending passively Black was signing his own death sentence. White’s kingside expansion is a winning plan and passive defence is destined to fail no matter how precise.  4. White’s expansion on the flanks was enabled by his pair of bishops and his already existing spatial edge in the centre. By having more space, White is able to gain yet more. } *

