{ @@HeaderStart@@Jan Smeets – Sergei Tiviakov, Netherlands 2013@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game is a modern example of White’s advantage after a symmetric structure transformation. Notice how White inevitably gains control of the c-file. } 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 d6 8. Be3 Bg7 9. f3 Be6 10. Rc1 O-O 11. Qd2 Qa5 { So far it is the same opening as the previous example, and now: } 12. b3 a6 { And now of course: } 13. Nd5 { This is similar to the previous example except the reply ...Qxa2 is no longer possible. } 13... Qd8 { Tiviakov probably realized his mistake by now, as keeping the queens on the board gives more practical chances to Black.   If  13...Qxd2+  14.Kxd2  Bxd5   or  14...Rae8  15.Be2  Nd7  16.h4  +=  15.cxd5  += we are back to the highly undesirable endgame from the previous example. } 14. Bb6 Qd7 15. Be2 Bxd5 { A necessary concession.   If instead  15...Rac8  16.O-O  += and Black has nothing useful to do other than capture on  d5  after all. } 16. cxd5 { We essentially have the previous game again, but now in the presence of queens. } 16... Rfc8 17. O-O Qe8 { The break  17...e6 ?!  18.dxe6  fxe6  works poorly as the presence of queens makes Black’s king vulnerable. } 18. Be3 Nd7 19. g3 { The careless  19.b4  Qd8  20.a4 ?!  is met by  20...a5 !  21.bxa5  Nc5  with counterplay for Black. } 19... Nc5 { Blocking the c-file for the moment, but this will not work in the long run as White is able to play b3-b4.   Better was  19...Rxc1  20.Rxc1  Rc8  21.Rc2  Qd8  22.Kg2  h5  23.b4  Kh7  24.Qc1  Rxc2  25.Qxc2  Bh6  26.Bf2 !  keeping the pair of bishops. After  26...a5  27.a3  axb4  28.axb4  += White is certainly better, though Black remains solid. } 20. Rc2 a5 21. Rfc1 b6 { The problem with Black’s 19th move is that the c-file will not stay blocked forever. Meanwhile, Black’s attempts to keep the file blocked are creating weaknesses that will persist forever. For example ...b7-b6 makes the b6-pawn and the c6-square weak. } 22. Qd1 Qf8 23. a3 { ± Preparing b3-b4. } 23... Rcb8 { But not:  23...Nxb3 ?  24.Rxc8  Rxc8  25.Rxc8  Qxc8  26.Qxb3  +- } 24. b4 axb4 25. axb4 Nb3 { The decisive mistake; the knight will not find a way out.   More stubborn was  25...Nd7  26.Bb5  Qd8  27.Qe2  Ra7  though White has many risk-free plans to play for a win, such as  28.Bc6 !?  h5  29.Kg2  Kh7  30.Ra2  Rxa2  31.Qxa2  ± following by an a-file invasion.   Not  25...Ra3 ?  26.bxc5  Rxe3  27.c6  followed by c6-c7 and  Ba6  winning. } 26. Rb1 Ra3 27. Rc6 Na1 28. Bxb6 { White is completely winning due to his extra pawn and the awkward location of the knight on a1. The rest of the game needs no comments. } 28... f5 29. Bd4 Rba8 30. e5 Bxe5 31. Bxe5 dxe5 32. b5 e4 33. b6 exf3 34. Bxf3 Qh6 35. b7 Qe3+ 36. Kh1 Kf7 37. bxa8=Q Rxa8 38. d6 { Final remarks  1. Black’s problems began by forgetting his opening move order, and allowing the strong 13.Nd5, which is an improved version of the previous game, as the ...Qxa2 reply is no longer available.  2. Despite his opening imprecision, Black had reasonable chances to hold the game by trading rooks on move 19.   3. Black’s biggest mistake was attempting to block the c-file with 19...Nc5, as White will gain this file anyway after the standard b3-b4. Black’s problem was that supporting his knight on c5 meant creating more weaknesses with 20...a5 and 21...b6, hence later when the c-file was finally unblocked, White gained a huge advantage. } *

