{ @@HeaderStart@@Nikolai Ninov – Dragoljub Velimirovic, Belgrade 2009@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objectives:  1. This game illustrates White’s attacking chances after an asymmetric transformation.  2. Note Black’s inability to create counterplay once the queenside is closed. } 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 d6 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Bd7 10. Qd2 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc6 12. f3 a5 13. b3 Nd7 14. Be3 Nc5 15. Rab1 { So far we are in the main line of the Accelerated Dragon, and now: } 15... b6 { This is a rare and low-scoring option.   The main line is  15...Qb6 } 16. Bd1 Ra7 17. a3 Qa8 18. Bc2 Rd8 19. Nd5 { White’s position is notably comfortable and now he invites Black to transform his position after: } 19... Bxd5 20. exd5 { We have reached the thematic structure.   If  20.cxd5  Rc8  21.Rfc1  Rac7  22.Bd1  b5  Black seems fine as he has gained some queenside space without weakening his position. } 20... Nd7 { If  20...a4  21.b4  Nd7  22.Bd3  Rc7  23.Rfd1  += White has a stable advantage, since the break  23...b5  is met by  24.Rbc1  bxc4  25.Rxc4  Rxc4  26.Bxc4  ± and the d5-pawn is well protected while Black’s a4-pawn is a target. } 21. f4 { This thematic move prepares f4-f5 with an attack, but it enables counterplay.   Better was  21.a4 !  preventing  ...a5-a4  , leaving Black without queenside activity. } 21... Qc8 { Returning the favour; Black misses his opportunity to complicate the game.   The break  21...a4 !  was necessary to obtain counterplay, and after  22.bxa4   22.b4 ?!  is met by  22...Rc7  23.Qe2  Rdc8  24.Bd3  b5  !!1 when White’s centre is trembling  22...Rc8  23.Rb4  Rac7  24.Bd3  Nc5  White’s extra pawn is clearly worthless. Still, there are chances for a kingside attack after  25.f5 !?  Nxa4  26.fxg6  hxg6  27.Qf2. } 22. a4 { ± This move rules out Black’s queenside reactions ...a5-a4 and ...b6-b5, and so White obtains a fully stable queenside. White is now able to conduct his kingside attack without distractions.   Instead  22.f5 ?  allows counterplay after  22...a4  !. } 22... Rb7 23. Rbe1 Re8 24. Rf3 { The immediate  24.f5  gives Black fewer options, and after  24...Ne5  25.Rf4  Bf6   or  25...Bh6  26.Rh4  Bxe3+  27.Rxe3  followed by  Reh3  26.h4  Kg7  27.Qf2  ± White can follow up with g2-g4 with deadly threats. } 24... e5 { Preventing f4-f5 with:  24...f5 !?  Can be met by:  25.g4 !  Forcing the opening of lines.  25...fxg4   Worse is  25...Rf8 ?  26.gxf5  gxf5  27.Qg2  Kh8  28.Rg3  when White’s attack is irresistible.  26.Rf2  Preparing f4-f5.  26...Bf6   26...Nf6  27.f5 !  gxf5  28.Bxf5  Qd8  29.Rg2  Kh8  30.Bd4  +-  27.Ref1  Nc5  28.f5 !  Keeping the e7-pawn fixed.   28.Rg2 ?  e6 !  28...g5  29.Bxg5  h5  30.h3 !  ± When Black is unable to keep the kingside closed.   Waiting with  24...Qd8  allows a strong attack after  25.f5 !  Ne5  26.Rg3  Bf6  27.Rf1.  Note how Black can only wait to be defeated:  27...Kg7  28.Rh3  Rh8  29.Bh6+  Kg8  30.Qe2  Rb8  31.g4  Rc8  32.Qe4  Rc7  33.g5  Bg7  34.Bxg7  Kxg7  35.Qh4 !  Black’s position is hopeless:  35...Kg8  36.fxg6  fxg6  37.Re3  Bringing the rook to the f-file.  37...Rb7  38.Re4  Rb8  39.Ref4  Qd7  40.Qh6  Black is tied to the defence of  f8.  40...Qe8  41.Be4 !  This will be followed by Bg2-h3-e6 – a very nice finish. } 25. dxe6 Rxe6 26. f5 { The attack continues. } 26... Re8 27. Ref1 Ne5 28. Rg3 Qc6 29. f6 { An alternative was  29.Bd4  d5  30.Qf4  threatening f5-f6:  30...Qf6  31.Kh1   but not  31.fxg6 ?  Nf3+ !  31...dxc4  32.fxg6  Qxf4  33.gxh7+  Kh8  34.Rxf4  ± } 29... Bh8 30. Qd4 { Threatening Be4 or Qh4 and then Rh3. } 30... Nd7 { The final mistake.   More stubborn was  30...d5 !  31.Qxd5  Qxd5  32.cxd5  ± though White has a clear extra pawn. } 31. Bxg6 { +-   Black resigns, as the following lines offer no escape:  31...hxg6   or  31...fxg6  32.f7+  Kf8  33.Qxh8+  Ke7  34.fxe8  =Q#  32.Rxg6+ !  And checkmate is unavoidable. For example:  32...Kh7   32...fxg6  33.f7+  33.Qh4+  Kxg6  34.Qh6#  Final remarks  1. The reader should note how in this game the capture 20.cxd5 would not have given much to White. It is necessary to know the pros and cons of both structures in order to choose correctly.  2. Once White stabilized the queenside with a3-a4, he had a free hand for a kingside attack. It is unlikely that Black could resist successfully. } *

